%% IOC Lifecycle — how one candidate IOCRecord moves from discovery to a
%% persisted, scored, classified IOC row, and how the framework never lets a
%% single malformed candidate crash extraction or silently lose a rejection
%% (constitution §1.7; docs/adr/0012-threat-intelligence-ioc-extraction-framework-shape.md).
%% Render with `mmdc -i ioc-lifecycle.mmd -o ioc-lifecycle.png`.

stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Discovered: IOCExtractionEngine finds a candidate\n(pattern scan or structured field)
    Discovered --> Validated: IOCValidator.validate() passes
    Discovered --> Rejected: IOCValidationError raised

    Validated --> Normalized: IOCNormalizer.normalize() [canonical form]
    Normalized --> Deduplicated: merged with any other candidate\nsharing (ioc_type, value)

    Deduplicated --> RuleEvaluated: DetectionRuleEngine.evaluate()\n[pattern/regex/threshold/composite]
    RuleEvaluated --> Scored: ThreatScoringEngine.score()\n+ ConfidenceCalculator.calculate()
    Scored --> Classified: ThreatClassificationEngine.classify()\n[benign|suspicious|malicious|unknown]
    Classified --> Attributed: EvidenceAttributionTracker.attribute()\n[line numbers, first/last seen]
    Attributed --> Persisted: IOCRepository.add()\n[status=ACTIVE]

    Rejected --> [*]: recorded in NormalizedThreatIntel.rejected_candidates\n(never silently dropped)
    Persisted --> [*]: available via IOCRepository.find_by_case /\nfind_by_evidence / find_by_value_and_type

    note right of Deduplicated
        Scoped to *within* one extraction run's
        candidate set — never cross-case/cross-
        evidence correlation (explicit scope cut,
        docs/adr/0012 point "Scope Cuts").
    end note

    note right of Persisted
        A later extraction run observing the same
        (ioc_type, value) can call
        IOCRepository.increment_occurrence() /
        mark_dismissed() / mark_false_positive() —
        analyst/pipeline workflow state, distinct
        from the ThreatCategory classification.
    end note
